"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047072","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-01-30","<p>​The Government remains strongly committed to promoting the respect for the human rights of all people, including indigenous people. We continue to work overseas and through the UN to improve the situation of indigenous people around the world. The UK has supported the adoption of the UN Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples, and the EU's Foreign Affairs Council conclusions on indigenous peoples.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047072/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-30T11:47:36.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047072/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047072/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-01-23","Indigenous Peoples","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking with his international counterparts to help safeguard the human rights and security of indigenous peoples overseas.","false","Biography information for Mr Paul Sweeney","Glasgow North East","Mr Paul Sweeney","211934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047073","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-01-28","<p>​The UK continues to push for greater international cooperation on climate change.</p><p>Last month at the Katowice COP 24 conference we reached an agreement on the rulebook for Paris Agreement implementation, a crucial step towards international accountability. However, all our assessments conclude that the current level of global ambition is still not enough to meet the Paris goals of just over three years ago. We need unprecedented and rapid action to reduce emissions and build resilience.</p><p>Minister of State for the Commonwealth and United Nations, Lord Ahmad, spoke just last week at the UN Security Council on the need to do more, and the UK is leading on Climate Resilience at the UN Secretary General's Climate Summit in September.</p><p>The UK takes the lead internationally on coal phase-out, renewable energy and zero emission vehicles, amongst others, but we are clear that in order to meet the Paris Agreement goals, all countries need to do more.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047073/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-28T16:31:05.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047073/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047073/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-01-23","Climate Change: International Cooperation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the progress on international cooperation on tackling climate change.","false","Biography information for Mr Paul Sweeney","Glasgow North East","Mr Paul Sweeney","211935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047074","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-01-31","<p>No direct assessment has been carried out. The Government takes biosecurity extremely seriously and aims to reduce the impacts of invasive non-native species on our natural environment, the economy and human health. As part of this, the Government works closely with the UK Squirrel Accord and forestry interests to implement the grey squirrel action plan for England and provides funding to the Animal and Plant Health Agency to explore the potential for developing a fertility control method for grey squirrels. We have made a commitment that our exit from the EU will not to erode protections for the environment.</p><p> </p><p>We therefore intend to uphold our commitment to the implementation of the EU Invasive Alien Species Regulation 2014 which requires us to manage the populations of widespread species such as grey squirrel and muntjac deer.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047074/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-31T13:15:13.81Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047074/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047074/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-01-23","Non-native Species","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the implementation of the Invasive Alien Species Order 2019 on the numbers of (a) grey squirrels and (b) muntjac deer.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","211687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047075","Department for International Trade","false","2019-02-01","<p>The process for appointing members to the STAG is almost complete and we expect to issue letters to successful candidates shortly.</p><p> </p><p>The Group will advise the Secretary of State for International Trade but will not set Government policy. This will not be a decision-making body and therefore we do not expect votes to take place.</p><p> </p><p>Members will be appointed to the Group for a defined period and will be expected to comply with the standards of behaviour set out in the Terms of Reference to be agreed by the Group at the first meeting. In conjunction with the Chairs of the Group, officials will provide recommendations to the Secretary of State on any changes to the Group’s membership. This will include looking at whether the Group is sufficiently representative. Any changes proposed will be made with reference to the criteria set out in the guidance published as part of the call for expressions of interest. Changes to membership will be published online.</p><p> </p><p>To facilitate an open and constructive discussion, members will be expected to conform to the highest standards of confidentiality and will be required to sign a non-disclosure agreement. Members will also be asked to act in the interests of the UK and not as a representative of their organisation.</p>","Meon Valley","George Hollingbery","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047075/answer",,,,,,"2019-02-01T14:59:19.593Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047075/answer","Biography information for Sir George Hollingbery","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047075/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-01-23","Strategic Trade Advisory Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, with reference to his Department's guidance entitled Call for expressions of interest in membership of the Strategic Trade Advisory Group, published on 16 July 2018, who will determine that members are no longer able to contribute effectively to the groups' deliberations prior to a member of the Strategic Trade Advisory Group having their membership revoked; and whether information on that decision will be made publicly available.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","211614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047076","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-01-31","<p>Defra and its agencies carry out farm inspections for a wide range of reasons including Animal Inspections, Disease Inspections, Environmental Inspections, Facility Inspections, Funding Scheme Inspections and Veterinary Medicine Inspections. These inspections form part of wider roles within each agency and we are therefore unable to provide the data as requested.</p><p> </p><p>These are the different kinds of farm inspections according to Gov.uk: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/farming-inspections" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/farming-inspections</a>.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047076/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-31T14:25:49.023Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047076/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047076/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-01-23","Farms: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many FTE Farm Inspectors have been employed in each region in each of the last five years figures are available.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","211635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047077","Department for International Trade","false","2019-02-01","<p>The process for appointing members to the STAG is almost complete and we expect to issue letters to successful candidates shortly.</p><p> </p><p>The Group will advise the Secretary of State for International Trade but will not set Government policy. This will not be a decision-making body and therefore we do not expect votes to take place.</p><p> </p><p>Members will be appointed to the Group for a defined period and will be expected to comply with the standards of behaviour set out in the Terms of Reference to be agreed by the Group at the first meeting. In conjunction with the Chairs of the Group, officials will provide recommendations to the Secretary of State on any changes to the Group’s membership. This will include looking at whether the Group is sufficiently representative. Any changes proposed will be made with reference to the criteria set out in the guidance published as part of the call for expressions of interest. Changes to membership will be published online.</p><p> </p><p>To facilitate an open and constructive discussion, members will be expected to conform to the highest standards of confidentiality and will be required to sign a non-disclosure agreement. Members will also be asked to act in the interests of the UK and not as a representative of their organisation.</p>","Meon Valley","George Hollingbery","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047077/answer",,,,,,"2019-02-01T14:58:59.47Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047077/answer","Biography information for Sir George Hollingbery","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047077/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-01-23","Strategic Trade Advisory Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what formal role the strategic trade advisory group will play in formulating trade policy.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","211615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047078","Department for International Trade","false","2019-02-01","<p>The process for appointing members to the STAG is almost complete and we expect to issue letters to successful candidates shortly.</p><p> </p><p>The Group will advise the Secretary of State for International Trade but will not set Government policy. This will not be a decision-making body and therefore we do not expect votes to take place.</p><p> </p><p>Members will be appointed to the Group for a defined period and will be expected to comply with the standards of behaviour set out in the Terms of Reference to be agreed by the Group at the first meeting. In conjunction with the Chairs of the Group, officials will provide recommendations to the Secretary of State on any changes to the Group’s membership. This will include looking at whether the Group is sufficiently representative. Any changes proposed will be made with reference to the criteria set out in the guidance published as part of the call for expressions of interest. Changes to membership will be published online.</p><p> </p><p>To facilitate an open and constructive discussion, members will be expected to conform to the highest standards of confidentiality and will be required to sign a non-disclosure agreement. Members will also be asked to act in the interests of the UK and not as a representative of their organisation.</p>","Meon Valley","George Hollingbery","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047078/answer",,,,,,"2019-02-01T14:58:40.6Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047078/answer","Biography information for Sir George Hollingbery","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047078/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-01-23","Strategic Trade Advisory Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how he plans to maintain confidentiality in respect of proceedings of the Strategic Trade Advisory Group; and whether members of that group will be prohibited from (a) discussing such proceedings and (b) publicly criticising aspects of trade policy that may have been considered in proceedings of the group.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","211616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047079","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-01-31","<p>Farming is a significant source of environmental pollution to water. The Government has long term strategies in place to address this. Leaving the EU provides the opportunity to change the way in which we support farmers to enhance the environment. The new Environmental Land Management system, underpinned by natural capital principles, will deliver many of the key outcomes set out in the 25 Year Environment Plan, including clean and plentiful water. River Basin Management Plans and the Environment Agency’s monitoring give a comprehensive assessment of water and ecological quality and the impact of agriculture.</p><p> </p><p>The Catchment Sensitive Farming programme works alongside Countryside Stewardship and water company catchment programmes to advise farmers on ways to reduce pollutant loadings and other sustainable water management objectives.</p><p> </p><p>As part of our 25 Year Environment Plan commitments we introduced the Farming Rules for Water[1] in England in April 2018 to prevent and reduce diffuse pollution from agriculture. The rules are outcome focused and require farmers to manage their land and farming activities in ways which keep soil on the land, match nutrients to crop, and soil needs, and keep livestock fertilisers and manures out of the water.</p><p> </p><p>Other water and agriculture regulations are being reviewed as part of work to improve water quality and streamline the regulatory baseline for agriculture. Findings and evidence from the Environment Audit Committee’s report [UK progress on Reducing Nitrate Pollution] and the Dame Glenys Stacey Review, together with commitments in the Clean Air Strategy and evidence from the implementation of the Farming Rules for Water, will be considered by that review to enable a more integrated approach to reducing pollution from agriculture in future.</p><p><br></p><p>[1] The Reduction and Prevention of Agricultural Diffuse Pollution (England) Regulations 2018</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047079/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-31T13:23:43.903Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047079/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047079/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-01-23","Farms: Pollution Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans he has to reduce diffuse pollution from farms to improve water quality.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","211636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047080","Home Office","false","2019-01-28","<p>As the Prime Minister announced on 21 January, there will be no fee for applications under the EU Settlement Scheme when we roll out the scheme in full by 30 March. Anyone who has applied during the pilot phase, or who does so, will have their fee reimbursed. The Home Office will set out further details in due course.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047080/answer",,,,,,"2019-01-28T16:59:16.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047080/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1047080/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-01-23","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if the Government will reimburse all reasonable administrative costs to EU citizens who apply for settled status.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","211619"
